The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The Czech mobile market is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers work at all among the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile phone providers SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How come prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a battle story.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100 %.
Mobile providers, on the other hand, would like to scoff at the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
This is often the responsibility of the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has very many opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequencies).
But there is still one possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile operators had to react to.
There were voices similar to those in the Czech Republic before the entry of companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market.
However, it has been shown that there is space for such providers and that these can be really successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the country's fifth largest provider.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, which, however, is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors in the UK.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to focus on an uncluttered target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Echte Kerle choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar approach could be adopted in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
The press spokesperson of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment based on most virtual providers.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service provision."
In the Czech Republic, mobile phone providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We speak of an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press spokesperson of the Penta financial group, says in a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Your interest in starting a virtual mobile provider has long shown the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve negotiating progress," said the press spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe we'll have better times.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a fully-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market has a large specificity vis-à-vis other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónica O2 press department in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the Czech market's specificity.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová's press spokesperson adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project that could be built on."
And she adds: "T-Mobile's network will hardly show up with a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a specific offer to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we regard as the best from the point of view of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to look for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider was called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that suppliers can draw on a string when it comes to something is also evidence of the long-standing development of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the time that U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidence of the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is right now as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player in the market itself and in particular its services would impose high demands."
However, in view of this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unfortunately, is not competent to intervene in economic competition in Czech countries, unlike the UK and other highly developed countries.
It has the sole responsibility to protect economic competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," says Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by representatives of the providers.
This is more than questionable by an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, ensuring that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristian Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is really shocking to note that the almost already touching agreement between the three mobile operators that results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gas price at the gas stations is certainly just coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive action in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their market behaviour.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably also missing from the telecoms regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in a similar way.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) demonstrate that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The shifting of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not been successful, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS only have to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are just several in the Czech mobile networks.
It is companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partly public.
Usually they are companies operating in the multi-level marketing sector.
Own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company is acting against the operator as a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a breach of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the corresponding society," answered Martina Kemrová on our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not go hand in hand with the controllers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
Indeed, the activities of these companies do not result in negligible profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for such kinds of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full access to it as normal mobile customers."
However, the ČTÚ would have to be at least strange.
In addition, another question opens up for the ÚOHS.
Before such an approach, mobile providers close their eyes, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the statement of the providers, they would not know of it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant price drop in the various services.
Virtually in all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened at these very moments, which did not try to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
If it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves all over the case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot lose the impression that in these cases ambiguity in the competences is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flu into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon emerges, the Czech mobile market may soon be reinvigorated.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will then finally call no more expensive than the rest of Europe.
