Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville worships a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and the mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and, when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert for oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters to emancipate women, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf and Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, a vegetarian and stood for the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the time between wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
`I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested to me this role, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We're not trying to tell about her life without keeping her Esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
`The dance of the butterfly' seemed to me, for example, like Guajira, or `the dance of the snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I have been told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area,' she claims.
The production is based on two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in `La puerto aberta'; and with flamenco champion Matilde Coral, who, exceptionally, wanted to work with one of her ex-students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honored.'
The production also includes musical composition and guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Jjarez, he takes on the role of companion of the artists who were Divas, in whom he repeatedly fell in love.'
This work also tells a certain way of telling about the life of this woman, who has been known in as far places as India, the United States or Russia and also throughout Europe, although she has normally lived in London.
`I wanted to call them back in memory, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a particular era and whose works are no longer appreciated today, and therefore she knows even less', says Bayón.
The performance takes place today at 20:30 at the Lope de Vega Theatre.
