Discussion - From Blood That Has Been Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her founding, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which was badly shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, during the 1980s the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross had contaminated national blood reserves with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched in February 1994 a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances which had led to such tragedy, and at drawing up guidelines to prevent a further catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to report, several provinces set up a committee at that time, whose aim was to develop a new system for the administration of blood canning in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec began her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood-supplied system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood canning and by working in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before she proudly emphasizes that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At this time we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we didn't have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, which states that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as it is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from individuals who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago there was no doubt that this disease was being transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the Nucleic Acid Tests (NST), which enable the donor to directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the donor’s blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests previously used.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, 12 million blood canned foods would have to be distributed before someone was infected with HIV.
As Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood canned products each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV was transmitted through a blood canned product.
I think you can feel comfortable these days when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore your health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We have to monitor continuously', Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supply in addition to a secure supply.
'The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood supply network, of which only 3% of Quebec's blood donation population is on average.'
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and who meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who make their blood available are not expected to be ill with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
With this 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and to get them to become regular donors.
Life today is so hectic that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in blood donation,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood canned but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively in case of serious burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, contains rich blood stem cells that can help treat severe diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the insertion of our thousands of umbilical cord blood samples, and we are planning to decrease more than a thousand annually.
`We should probably start by making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', Dr. Décary further explains, which describes this program of navel cord loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all of Quebec's hospitals.
