The psychology of oversupply - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the error bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to compete in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the others took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brainbone, was measured at the loss of the auction, in which the enemy’s oversupply plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase was explained by the avoidance of an overreaction to the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group have carried out additional research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised 15 dollar reward, in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was that the emphasis on the one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypotheses expressed by neurologists, the members of the "opposite to lose" group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results can not be derived from previous economic theory.
In fact, they have only been able to justify the behaviour observed at auctions with the pleasure of winning or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological processes, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various viruses that cause infectious liver disease.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated foods or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, cleavage secretion or saliva).
Travellers are advised to receive vaccination against the viruses A and B at least, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, yellow fever occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine is dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from hepatitis B-induced, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer without treatment.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the pathogen is hesitantly destroying the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Timely prevention, such as regular monitoring, is therefore essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, which bans the risk of infection and prevents the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, which is held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
