Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, those of the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired in the creation of new accident prevention systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic system of type BR23C, a mini-car, equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield," said Kazuhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology-PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To simulate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a field of vision of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of seconds, and the autobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place instinctively.
"If it wasn't, the Autobot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autoboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology is the most internal and vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is currently considered unavoidable within the accidents.
The entire process must reflect the behaviour of bees when avoiding other bees.
And this must end in a fraction of a second.
However, unlike the bees, the deviation can not be made up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the reversibility of the tyres.
While the bees here are infinitely open to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use the autobot only the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous maneuvers, so that it constantly only takes a handful of KB Memory.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production in the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
