The high-level conference was opened by Mr Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Mr Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the participants were representatives of governments, European social partners, and the most important European legal protection and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
As reported by the Press Office of the MEPs of Fidesz, Járóka has pointed out that apart from discrimination in job search, Roma would be excluded from the labour market mainly because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youth have no secondary education, and due to poor primary education, only a small part of them can reach a university degree".
Járóka also stressed that education is a fundamental human right which would have a key role to play in asserting other human rights.
Investment in the early training of Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU Member States.
In the view of the honourable Members, it is important that these links become as broad a circle as possible - Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma student starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; and through income and turnover taxes they contribute to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, the Roma must be guaranteed the right to high-quality education - the poor and segregated education must be discontinued" - says Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a joint, goal-oriented and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of deregulation in the education sector, which is essential if the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are to be properly complied with.
"We must break through the vicious circle of poverty, segregation, and unemployment and give Roma children democratic opportunities to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens," Járóka demanded.
Since the Berlin Congress last year, the summit has been organised annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the advance of the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom of discrimination at European, but also at national level, within the meaning of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
