Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy 2500 accidents at work, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For 2007, the data of Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all provinces of Italy is going to attend the 58th National Day for the Victims of Work Accidents to draw the attention of the social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data spread by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention at work is," confirmed the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to job prevention, to the protection of injured workers, to support the families of the victims and to raise awareness of public opinion".
"An outrageous "Basta" has risen to this point; understandably in the case of tragedies that, in terms of their size, trigger some vortex in the media and public participation. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is in any case also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
A special importance is attached to the numerous initiatives for a more direct raising of awareness in schools by young people who feed on the labour market.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to distract from its social seriousness. One must put into force and improve a legislative standard.
On the other hand, the President of the Chamber of Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths represents an urgent social emergency, which insults the conscience of all of us and forces all of our institutions to work towards firm rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data from the accidents at work seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not rule out that the number of accidents at work is too high," said President of Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you believe that you are doing too little to deal with the phenomenon of accidents, and you can fight it through various actions.
