The Elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the 700 billion dollar savings package of the White House: a large part of the Americans was and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This confirms yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis has progressed beyond the Republican Party, which is becoming more and more divided into its old and moderate East Coast Seele, which always favoured the state institutions and the business community and those neoconservatives who are hostile to "the Washington" and the financial world and, above all, win voters in the south and the centre of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise, above all, to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond, will be affected by these.
Both in the States and in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the long-afraid events, which, under these new conditions, finally take shape and come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unheard renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with abroad and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This is an immediate political problem for governments: how to deal with the families concerned, which is an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have gone awry in itself and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, because of its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common way.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, distribution of aid funds: ever since the crisis became more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the funds, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two non-exhaustive conditions – under certain circumstances – on which otherwise no international organisation and no market will be able to rely in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the state-national element is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that is most recently associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is right now, when we were so convinced of having long ago entered a networked empire, into a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, the intangible, that we need to determine at once how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
Although they can all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are still extremely connected to a closely defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in favour of another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil - free area.
I now come to the second innovation, which, however, requires a short shift.
Those who say territory, who government, who politics, thus also say leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, so the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of dismay over the existing leaders, especially those of the economy, who have emerged as inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an impatience, an image of inefficiency, a feeling of distance, all directed towards an entire class of managers of the Western countries.
It seems that the conviction among large parts of the population paves the way for it to be not only the deeds of social elites, but already their world of ideas, their Way of Life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is the majority as ever more alien and superior.
The demand for leadership thus nourishes underground a forced but powerful movement of the abduction of the leading class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the immediate reversal of the collective state of mind of the past: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party in the UK, the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value of what is going on in the lower social strata of the West today and is still being strengthened from the financial crisis and driven to overdimensionality.
In view of all of this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
