Medicines: never take fruit juice
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and their vitamin richness, especially in summer, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on their absorption by the body.
David Bailey, professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaging as well as fresh fruit juices associated with medication intake. At the 236th American Chemical Society meeting in Philadelphia, he again called for an alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption of certain vital medicines, so that they are practically eliminated and the health of the patients is endangered.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines such as antibiotics, antiarrhythmics, cardiovasculars, anxiolytics and neurologics, up to toxic levels.
MEDICALS IN DRIVER – The same agency of the medicine had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago about the dangers of this mixture, and stressed that what is being drunk in conjunction with medicines such as diazepan or methadone.
IT IS NOT GRAFFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of substances inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
The appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "These results are usually transmitted immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is recommended that you always read the package leaflet and, if there are any uncertainties, do not hesitate to ask a pharmacist or a doctor," the Ansa-agent expert stresses.
