Open Office, it appears the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The date of publication of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has arrived; the Open Source software is gaining an ever larger number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now sparsely designed start menu, a basic compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system is finally achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
In addition, attention has been paid to compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as those that allow you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which facilitates e.g. sending via email. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphic editing modules while at the same time preserving the original appearance of the page.
Thus, you can now also generate "hybrid" PDF files, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a text processing system.
Cooperation is one of the most improved elements of the applications: Tables can now be edited by different users more easily, avoiding conflicts with changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question to ensure a better correction process.
Some companies are just about to publish various functions of OpenOffice on the internet (on the cloud), while the definitive result is to be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download on the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0/download300.html. Thus, it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
Upon request you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
However, if freedom of charge can be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also in the business area where OpenOffice the big throw could succeed: after all, various public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is no lack of even a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, to create presentations such as PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of known access; and last but not least Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded at already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
