Good-bye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This image of director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of large multi-story complexes in the periphery, means death in the long term for the single-room cinema in the centre. A process that appears not only irrevocably and irrevocably, but also carries the trains of a cultural crime.
These are mostly historical places full of memories, "It is like losing a friend with whom one has travelled a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a well-lost cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas had to close; these coins paid mostly the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions include Emilia Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy has led the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and in Emilia Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first of all the receipt of the already existing one, because closing a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit instead of the old one a multiplex cinema in the periphery.
And here remains the missing bill for the fund of the trade union outside the eight: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
To preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be needed in the year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of the fears about the old cinema halls, has decided to protect it by means of an agreement between the community and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax incentives for cinema operators and benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be possible to drive into the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also park at more favourable parking fees.
"It is a pleasant initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to align something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because finally the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to start the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side in order not to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations by the Antimafia authorities of Calabria against the mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in Mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been convicted for entanglement in criminal associations of the mafia, at that time at a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Despite any kind of moral and legal standard," the lawyers wrote, "the two local authorities had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities."
"This made it possible for the Mafia Group – the judges say – to enter the City Halls officially and to agree on public administration policy."
The president of the Calabria Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region it is "all but an exception to encounter links between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such connections are practically unavoidable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, with which the Clan Piromalli police decapitated.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and also at that time due to alleged links between organized crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the Middle Right Coalition after the election of May 2006.
He shouted scandal as the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He was interested in this in the Deputy Minister Marco Minniti, who accused him of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges, in connection with this morning's arrest warrant, said that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request an amendment to the A3 project.
From a hearing campaign in connection with the Dal Torrione case investigations, the willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli, has shown that the public administration measures have become identical with the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the great ones run up
It is an undefiled source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now does this seem to understand the great energy companies of the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that all look at now and also seek to occupy, such as giants as Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and examined for 70 years; these studies have not by chance intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy demand could be covered by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the current energy produced by nuclear power plants.
There are also currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are focusing on marine energy generation.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – according to the speaker of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs the possibility of working with us."
It is a question of obtaining approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off Alaska's coast.
This is an unestimated sign, especially when we consider that oil is still being promoted by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts speak of a technology that is still emerging, not least since the last doubts have not yet been resolved by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, there is a need for technologies with a far greater impact on the environment.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
It drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent via underwater pipelines to the coast.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot with the help of underground turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movement during the tides drives the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Research, a particular interest deserves immediately the potential that is in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more trustworthy power source.
It is precisely tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are planned for 2009.
